GREY LEAF SPOT, MAIZE - KENYA (RIFT VALLEY)
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>

[see: Grey leaf spot, maize - Zimbabwe 990206111530]
Date: Fri, 10 Dec 1999 01:20:07 -0500
From: "Marjorie P. Pollack" <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: The Nation, Nairobi, Kenya Wed 8 Dec 1999 [edited]

An alert has been sounded over an outbreak of a disease said to have
attacked this year's maize seed crop. A Kenya Plant Health Inspection
Service official said the disease, known as gray leaf spot, had affected the
seed crop in the major maize-growing districts, and possibly the commercial
crop as well.
Aldai MP Kiptum Choge claimed that maize seed in the Rift Valley had been
infected, and warned of crop failure in the next season if urgent measures
were not taken by the Ministry of Agriculture. He said farmers were likely
to incur losses if the seeds were not withdrawn, adding that seeds should be
imported from South Africa to avert a food crisis. Many producers, he said,
had resorted to planting untreated maize since seed companies had become
unreliable and the cost of seeds unaffordable.
Participants at the two-day workshop called on the government to fund
research on crop varieties that were high-producing and disease-resistant.
The cost of seeds should also be subsidised, they said.
Rift Valley Provincial Commissioner Francis Baya said of the 1.4 million
bags of maize produced in the country, 500 000 were from Rift Valley.
