[According to Ward et al., 1999 Gray leaf spot, a disease of global
importance in maize production. Phytopathology 83:884-895, gray leaf spot
caused by the fungus _Cercospora zeae-maydis_, is one of the most
significant
yield-limiting diseases of maize worldwide. First reported in 1924, it
poses a serious threat to maize production in the major maize-producing
regions of the USA and Africa. It has become pandemic in Africa following
its appearance in Kwazulu Natal, South Africa in 1988. The disease is also
reported to occur in Brazil, Colombia, Peru, Trinidad, Costa Rica, Mexico,
Venezuela, and China.
Disease induction is highly dependent on high humidity, and disease
management is difficult once the pathogen is established. Development of
high-yield, locally adapted gray leaf spot tolerant hybrids is probably the
best way to manage the disease. Gray leaf spot disease is particularly
significant because maize is the principal food staple for the indigenous,
rural populations of Africa, threatening food security in many African
countries. - Mod.DH]
